# HyperFisher — Thesis Repository

Fisher-Orthogonal Projected Natural Gradient Descent applied to Hypernetwork-based Continual Learning.

**Jakub Michałowski** — Thesis, Department of Cognitive Science and Artificial Intelligence, Tilburg University

---

## Repository Structure
```
./
├── HyperFisher/          # Main project (see below)
├── gym/                  # Early-stage side project: benchmarking SSMs vs Transformers
│                         # on memory/recall-intensive RL tasks
├── misc/                 # Thesis writing, poster, proposal, and other residuals
├── FOPNG/                # Reference implementation — FOPNG paper (Garg et al., 2026)
├── fop/                  # Reference implementation — related paper
├── hypercl/              # Reference implementation — Hypernetworks for CL (von Oswald et al.)
├── toy_playground/       # Scratch experiments and prototyping
└── .gitmodules           # Submodules for reference codebases
```

---

## Main Project: `HyperFisher/`
```
HyperFisher/
├── main.py               # Entry point — CLI for all training runs
├── main.sh               # Example run scripts
├── sweep.sh              # W&B sweep launcher
├── sweep.yaml            # W&B sweep config (hyperparameter search)
├── hyper_network.py      # HyperNetwork implementation
├── mlp_base.py           # Plain MLP target network
├── utils.py              # Shared utilities
├── optimizers/           # Training loops
│   ├── fopng.py          #   FOPNG — Fisher-Orthogonal Projected Natural Gradient
│   ├── ewc.py            #   EWC — Elastic Weight Consolidation baseline
│   └── adam.py           #   Adam baseline
├── tasks/                # Task generators
│   ├── split_mnist.py    #   Split-MNIST (5 binary tasks)
│   ├── permuted_mnist.py #   Permuted-MNIST
│   └── split_cifar10.py  #   Split-CIFAR-10
├── visualizations/       # Plotting scripts (trajectory graphs etc.)
├── data/                 # Downloaded datasets (auto-populated)
└── wandb/                # W&B run logs (auto-populated)
```

### Method

FOPNG combines two ideas:

1. **Natural gradient descent** — preconditions updates with the inverse Fisher information matrix, respecting the true Riemannian geometry of parameter space rather than Euclidean distance.

2. **Orthogonal projection** — after each task, stores the gradient in a memory matrix G. New updates are projected onto the Fisher-orthogonal complement of G, enforcing a hard constraint that prior task outputs cannot be disturbed.

Applied to a **hypernetwork** (which generates task-specific weights from a small shared parameter set φ), this keeps both the Fisher matrix and gradient memory compact regardless of target network size.

### Baselines

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| Adam | Naive baseline, no forgetting protection |
| EWC | Elastic Weight Consolidation — diagonal Fisher regularizer in Euclidean space |

### Benchmarks

| Benchmark | Tasks | Notes |
|-----------|-------|-------|
| Split-MNIST | 5 binary (0v1, 2v3, ...) | Entry-level sequential learning |
| Permuted-MNIST | 10+ permutations | Long-horizon retention |
| Split-CIFAR-10 | 5 tasks, natural images | Higher visual complexity |

### Usage
```bash
# Split-MNIST with FOPNG + EWC + Adam
python main.py \
  --task split_mnist \
  --methods fopng ewc adam \
  --epochs 5 \
  --lr 1e-3 \
  --model HyperNetwork

# Run a W&B hyperparameter sweep
bash sweep.sh
```

**Key CLI arguments:**

| Argument | Default | Description |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `--task` | required | `split_mnist`, `permuted_mnist`, `split_cifar10` |
| `--methods` | `fopng adam` | One or more of `fopng`, `ewc`, `adam`, `ogd`, `fng` |
| `--model` | `HyperNetwork` | `HyperNetwork` or `MLP` |
| `--epochs` | `10` | Epochs per task |
| `--lr` | `1e-3` | Learning rate |
| `--grads_per_task` | `40` | Gradient directions stored per task |
| `--max_directions` | `80` | Cap on total memory matrix columns |
| `--embedding_dim` | `4` | Task embedding dimension |

Experiment tracking is handled via [Weights & Biases](https://wandb.ai). Runs are logged automatically on launch.

